Analysis of Airbnb and Real Estate data

This is the second part of the project, here is the first part In the “With_Real_Estate” document, I showed how I obtained the data from a website of Real Estate website. Here I start from downloading the datasets from Airbnb Data Collection.

Obtain the Airbnb Data

I chose Florence, Turin and Venice data from June 2017, and created a combined the three datasets into a compact one “AirbnbItaly”.

Florence06 <- read.csv(("florence_1366_2017-06-22.csv")) %>%
  mutate(city = "F") #%>%
  #This next line might be useful for future projects, not for this one in particular
  #select(room_id,room_type,city,reviews,overall_satisfaction,accommodates,bedrooms,price, neighborhood, latitude,longitude) 
Turin06 <- read.csv("turin_1407_2017-06-28.csv")%>%
  mutate(city = "T")
Venice06 <- read.csv("venice_1361_2017-06-22.csv") %>%
  mutate(city = "V")
AirbnbItaly <-  
  rbind(Venice06, Florence06, Turin06)

Then I grouped by the city name and neighborhood and summarized the dataset using the median price. The median is useful for the comparisons. I also renamed the variable “neighborhood” into “Areas” in order to not get confused with the variable in the scraped dataset.

FinalAirbnb <- AirbnbItaly %>% 
  group_by(city, neighborhood) %>%
  summarise(medianAirbnb = median(price)) %>%
  arrange(desc(medianAirbnb)) %>%
  rename('Areas' = 'neighborhood')

Load Real Estate dataset

First, I loaded the dataset that I had previously exported in the first part of the project I also wrote key.cvs in order to match the neighborhoods from the scraped dataset with the Areas in the Airbnb dataset. The matching was done manually through research conducted on Wikipedia.

Estate <- read.csv("table.csv") %>%
  select(neigh, price)
key <- read.csv("key.csv")
Joined <- key %>%
  full_join(Estate, by = "neigh") %>%
  select(city, Areas, neigh, price) %>%
  rename('neighborhood' = 'neigh') %>%
  rename('estateprice' = 'price') %>%
  na.omit()

I calculated the median for the real estate data too.

FinalEstate <- Joined %>%
  group_by(city, Areas) %>%
  summarise(medianEstate_inthousands = median(estateprice)) %>%
  arrange(desc(medianEstate_inthousands)) %>%
  select(medianEstate_inthousands, Areas, city)

Some distribution plots

To give an idea of how the both datasets are distributed, I used ggplot from DataComputing package. We can see that most of the Airbnb rentals tend to cheapest in Turin and most expensive in Venice.

AirbnbItaly %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=price, group=city, color=city)) +
  geom_density(adjust=2) +
  xlim(0, 400)

AirbnbItaly %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=city, y=price)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  ylim(0,400)

The same plots are shown for the Real Estate data and the results are slighly different: while Turin has on average the cheapest house prices, Venice does not have as the most expensive houses. Florence has on average the most expensive houses. This is an interesting point to consider for our final analysis.

Combine the scraped with the Airbnb dataset

Now, on our last step: combining the two scraped dataset (which was previously matched through they key) with the Airbnb dataset.

Airbnb_Estate <- FinalAirbnb %>%
  full_join(FinalEstate, by = "Areas") %>%
  select(Areas, city.x, medianAirbnb, medianEstate_inthousands) %>%
  arrange(desc(medianEstate_inthousands))

Where should I buy a house?

Everything done so far was just “getting the data”. Now we can answer our original question:“Where should I buy a house to be more profitable by renting it on Airbnb?” There are some assumptions to be made:

  • Every price listing on Airbnb stay constant throughout the years

  • Every listeing on Airbnb is rented out every day

With those two assumptions, we will new ratio variable between the Airbnb price * 365 (amount rented out in euro per one year) and divide it by the estate price (price from which I bought the price in thousands of euro) for each neighborhood . This ratio will represent “how many years it takes to gain back the amount spent on buying the house”.

The goal is to observe if there is a certain neighborhood, and if possible, even a certain city in which this ratio will be the lowest.

Airbnb_Estate <- Airbnb_Estate %>%
  mutate(ratio = (medianAirbnb * 100) / medianEstate_inthousands) %>%
  arrange((ratio))
knitr::kable(head(Airbnb_Estate))

Seems “Centro-Crocetta” (which is downtown in Turin!) and Isolott o-Legnaia (an Area in Fl orence) are the two best pl aces to invest, while 
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data=Airbnb_Estate,aes(x=medianAirbnb,y=medianEstate_inthousands))+geom_point()+aes(colour=city.x)

From this final scatter plot, which represents the ratio variable, we can see that 1. Turin Airbnb Rentals and Real Estate Prices tend to be both very cheap, but there is one neighborhood (Centro Crocetta) that seems very profitable 2. Venice is either very cheap or very expensive 3. Florence overall is the best one in terms of profitability

So to answer our final question: If we want to buy one house from one specific neighborhood, we should choose Centro Crocetta from Turin If we want to choose one city, overall both Turin and Florence are the most profitable, because they have on average lower ratio, which means that they take less time to earn back the amount of money spent originally on buying the property.
